&lt;h1 id="killing-the-process">Killing the process&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>Using your obtained &lt;code>process ID&lt;/code> (in this example it will be &lt;code>81&lt;/code>), run the following SQL to kill the process:
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-tsql" data-lang="tsql">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="k">KILL&lt;/span>&lt;span class="w"> &lt;/span>&lt;span class="mi">81&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Be warned, this might take a while. If everything went well, you will have things moving again.&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 id="what-if-this-doesnt-work">What if this doesn&amp;rsquo;t work?&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>It could be that things are unable to get started again. In that case, you will have one more trick in the book: Azure support. If you open a ticket with them, they can restart your SQL serverless pool.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>